<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-782-890  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 782 890.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Sept 26 1989 v3 n34 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple, Microsoft font alliance goads Adobe into about-face.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lehman, Cliff.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The competition between Apple Computer Inc and Adobe Systems Incover outline font technology intensifies with the announcement ofa cooperative agreement between Apple and Microsoft Corp. Theagreement calls for Microsoft to license Apple's Royal outlinefont technology for OS-2 development while Apple will acquireMicrosoft's Postscript-clone technology for employment in Appleprinters.andP;  The move represents a competitive challenge to Adobe'sPostscript font and printer technology.andP;  Analyst Jonathan Seyboldsaid the announcement would 'change the structure of the industryfor years to come.' Adobe responded with plans to publish completePostscript language specifications in the 1st Qtr 90.andP;  Apple andMicrosoft called the agreement a boon to users and called forAdobe to join them in supporting Apple outline fonts.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (contracts)Microsoft Corp. (contracts)Adobe Systems Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    ADBE; MSFT; AAPL.andO;Product:   PostScript (Printer software) (marketing).andO;Topic:     CompetitionCooperative AgreementFontsStrategic Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Cliff LehmanandM;San Francisco -- The rift between Adobe Systems Inc. and Apple over controlof the outline font technology widened last week as Adobe struggled to defendits leadership against an axis formed by Apple and Microsoft Corp.andM;The battle started with a press conference -- hastily arranged after weeks ofintense negotiations -- where Apple and Microsoft announced a cross-licenseagreement to trade type and printer technology (see MacWEEK, Sept. 19).andM;The agreement calls for Microsoft to license Apple's outline font technology,code-named Royal, for use in OS/2 Presentation Manager.andP;  In return, Applegets Microsoft's PostScript-clone technology for use in future Appleprinters.andP;  The upshot is the establishment of a potential standard competingwith the de facto industry standard set by Adobe with its PostScript font andprinter technology.andM;The Apple-Microsoft announcement &quot;will change the structure of the industryfor years to come,&quot; said Jonathan Seybold, publisher of the Seybold Report onDesktop Publishing.andM;John Warnock, Adobe CEO, responded with an unexpected announcement that drewripples of applause at the opening session of the Seybold Computer PublishingConference andamp; Exposition here.andM;In an about-face of Adobe's policy of keeping its font technology secret,Warnock said, &quot;Adobe will publish the complete specifications of thePostScript language, including Type 1 format&quot; in the first quarter of 1990.andM;Warnock continued with a fervent defense of the PostScript standard thatsparked pointed exchanges between industry giants Steve Jobs, chairman ofNeXT Inc., and Bill Gates, CEO of Microsoft (see story, Page 1).andM;Some industry analysts questioned whether Apple has given up a competitiveadvantage by offering Microsoft its outline font technology.andP;  But JohnSculley, Apple CEO said, &quot;Apple will keep ways of maintaining differentiation(between the platforms).andP;  We will build our distinctiveness on top of that(common font technology).&quot;andM;Apple and Microsoft touted the alliance as good for users.andP;  &quot;This is awin-win situation for all parties concerned, starting with the customers,&quot;Sculley said.andM;Asked how the Apple announcement would affect Adobe, Sculley said, &quot;Adobe hasexcellent application development, and they are an important font vendor.andP;  Wehope they will join in supporting Apple outline fonts.&quot;andM;Adobe stock has dropped sharply since rumors of the Apple-Microsoft dealstarted circulating two weeks ago (see related story, this page).andM;&quot;Royal doesn't mean that Adobe will go out of business or even necessarilyshrink,&quot; said Stewart Alsop, editor of P.C.andP;  Letter, an industry newsletterin Redwood City, Calif.andP;  &quot;But they are no longer the central player.&quot;andM;There is another shoe yet to drop.andP;  IBM is the controlling player now, Jobssaid.andP;  &quot;Apple made a mistake with the Royal font format.andP;  IBM will eitherbail Apple out,&quot; or go with PostScript.andM;&quot;IBM believes Royal technology is sound,&quot; said Nick Donofrio, vice presidentof IBM's Advanced Workstation Division.andP;  &quot;It will be in OS/2 in the future.&quot;andM;However, Donofrio added, other IBM platform divisions have not evaluatedRoyal.andM;Microsoft will also make room in OS/2 for other font formats such asCompugraphic's Intellifont, Gates said.andP;  Potential formats include SunMicrosystems' OpenFont, Bitstream Inc.'s Speedo, and The Company's Nimbus Q,as well as Adobe's.andM;Apple on the other hand adamantly refuses to support Adobe's Type 1 or anyother type format on the Mac.andP;  &quot;We will support only Royal on the Mac,&quot; saidJim Gable, product manager at Apple.andM;Although Apple will not make room for other font technologies on its system,Apple promised that System 7.0 will continue to support printing Adobe Type 1fonts on existing PostScript machines.andP;  But Adobe no longer intends to builda translator to convert Royal fonts to Adobe Type 1 fonts, as it promisedwhen Apple revealed Royal last May, Warnock said.andM;Calling Royal technology &quot;vaporware&quot; and inviting people to look at AdobeType Manager (Adobe software that processes outline fonts for the Mac screen)running on the Mac, Warnock said, &quot;Adobe is quite happy to compete on thequality of goods we produce.andP;  We are not going to blow smoke and mirrors atyou.&quot;andM;ATM for the Mac is set to ship in October, and a version for OS/2 is beingprepared now, Warnock said.andM;Gates offered no specific dates for the availability of Royal for OS/2.andP;  n</TEXT></DOC>